tebook.com/Algebra2/Polynomials/syndiv3frac.jpg" width=3D"389" height=3D"18=
9" alt=3D"synfrac"></td>
                           <td width=3D"46%" valign=3D"top" class=3D"TimesB=
lack14"><div align=3D"center">We know that when reducing a fraction, you mu=
st divide <strong>BOTH </strong>the numerator and the denominator by the sa=
me value, to maintain an equivalent fraction.<br>
                             The same is true when working with algebraic f=
ractions.<br>
                             This is what went wrong when we divided by 2! =
 <br>
                             We did not divide the <strong>numerator </stro=
ng>by 2. </div></td>
                         </tr>
                       </tbody></table></td>
                     </tr>
                     <tr>
                       <td colspan=3D"2" valign=3D"top" class=3D"TimesBlack=
14"><div align=3D"center">
                         Let's try synthetic division again. But this time,=
 we will divide BOTH the numerator and denominator by 2.<br>
                           <img src=3D"https://mathbitsnotebook.com/Algebra=
2/Polynomials/synC.png" alt=3D"synC" width=3D"500" height=3D"85"><br>
                           Much better!  Now, we have an equivalent problem=
 where the denominator  resembles what we have seen previously in our synth=
etic division questions (a <strong>leading coefficient of one</strong>).
<table width=3D"100%" border=3D"0">
                           <tbody><tr>
                             <td width=3D"50%" valign=3D"middle"><div align=
=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://mathbitsnotebook.com/Algebra2/Polynomials/s=
tndivNA.png" alt=3D"syndivNA" width=3D"278" height=3D"270"></div></td>
                             <td width=3D"50%" valign=3D"top" class=3D"Time=
sBlack14"><p>This new answer is almost a perfect match to the <span class=
=3D"TimesDarkRed14"><strong>actual answer</strong></span>, but what is goin=
g on with the remainder?<br>
                               This remainder is <span class=3D"TimesRed14"=
><strong>equivalent</strong></span> to -17/(2<em>x</em> + 1).  Simply multi=
ply the top and bottom by 2. </p>
                              <p align=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://mathb=
itsnotebook.com/Algebra2/Polynomials/sym3fa.png" alt=3D"syn3fa" width=3D"31=
3" height=3D"167"><br>
                                <span class=3D"TimesRed14">This is a match =
to the actual answer. </span></p></td>
                           </tr>
                         </tbody></table>
                         <table width=3D"100%" border=3D"0">
                           <tbody><tr>
                             <td><table width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" class=
=3D"blackborder">
                               <tbody><tr>
                                 <td width=3D"16%" valign=3D"bottom"><img s=
rc=3D"https://mathbitsnotebook.com/Algebra2/Images/HintGalMB.jpg" width=3D"=
111" height=3D"110" alt=3D"hint"></td>
                                 <td width=3D"84%" class=3D"TimesBlack14">S=
ynthetic division can get "messy" when the divisor has a leading coefficien=
t other than one. It will be a good idea to <strong>CHECK</strong> your syn=
thetic division, in these situations, by using long division. This will gua=
rantee that you always get the correct answer.<em> Be careful when the lead=
ing coefficient of the divisor is not 1!</em></td>
                               </tr>
                             </tbody></table></td>
                           </tr>
                         </tbody></table>                      =20
                       </div></td>
                     </tr>
                   </tbody></table>
                   <br>
                   <br>
                 </div>
               </div>
